action taken:

*Opened Windows Firewall configuration tool.
*Listed all current firewall rules to see existing settings.
*Added a rule to block inbound traffic on Telnet (port 23).
*Added a rule to block inbound traffic on HTTP (port 80).
*Tested connectivity to port 23 and port 80 to verify they were blocked.
*Added a rule to allow SSH (port 22) for remote access.
*Removed the block rule for Telnet (port 23).
*Removed the block rule for HTTP (port 80).

List all firewall rules
Use the command: “netsh advfirewall firewall show rule name equals all”
Block Telnet on port 23
Use the command: “netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name equals Block Telnet, direction equals in, action equals block, protocol equals TCP, local port equals 23”
Block HTTP on port 80
Use the command: “netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name equals Block HTTP, direction equals in, action equals block, protocol equals TCP, local port equals 80”
Allow SSH on port 22
Use the command: “netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name equals Allow SSH, direction equals in, action equals allow, protocol equals TCP, local port equals 22”
Delete the Telnet block rule
Use the command: “netsh advfirewall firewall delete rule name equals Block Telnet”
Delete the HTTP block rule
Use the command: “netsh advfirewall firewall delete rule name equals Block HTTP”
Test connectivity to blocked ports
To test Telnet on port 23, use: “Test-NetConnection to localhost on port 23”
To test HTTP on port 80, use: “Test-NetConnection to localhost on port 80”
